The paper presents a Bayesian multi-objective optimization algorithm that uses a gradient Gaussian Process model to calculate the probability of a point satisfying preference-order constraints. This involves a combination of machine learning, optimization, and decision-making techniques, which are commonly found in the sub-categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), and decision making (cs.DM). The paper also mentions the use of the algorithm in real-world problems, which suggests that it may be relevant to the sub-categories of systems and control (cs.SY) and neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE).
